t harder for him to be heard” (Lines 2, Para. 9)?","textExplain":"定位：据题干信息词定位于第九段。\n解析：第九段说，Maybe there is an Einstein out there today“当今世界可能有爱因斯坦这样的人”，but it would be a lot harder for him to be heard，“但他要成名很困难”。下文以爱因斯坦提交他关于时空的论文的方式为例，在末尾以格林的话为总结：我们都会受到这样的邮件，但是我们会把它们归为垃圾邮件。","videoExplainUrl":"","rightOpt":3,"userOpt":0,"answerJsons":[{"option":1,"content":"People have to compete in order to get their papers published."},{"option":2,"content":"It is hard for a scientist to have his papers published today."},{"option":3,"content":"Papers like Einstein’s would unlikely get published today."},{"option":4,"content":"Nobody will read papers on apparently ridiculous theories."}]},{"id":102984,"title":"When he submitted his papers in 1905, Einstein _______.","textExplain":"定位：据题干信息词1905定位于倒数第三段。\n解析：倒数第三段第二句中说这些论文的作者是a virtual unknown，“一个实际上不出名的人”，即B选项中was little known“没什么名气”，故B选项为正确答案。","videoExplainUrl":"","rightOpt":2,"userOpt":0,"answerJsons":[{"option":1,"content":"forgot to make footnotes and citations"},{"option":2,"content":"was little known in academic circles"},{"option":3,"content":"was known as a young genius in math calculations"},{"option":4,"content":"knew nothing about the format of academic papers"}]}]},{"id":4976,"name":"2011.6 Passage One","content":"    At the heart of the debate over illegal immigration lies one key question: are immigrants good or bad for the economy? The American public overwhelmingly thinks they're bad. Yet the consensus among most economists is that immigration, both legal and illegal, provides a small net boost to the economy. Immigrants provide cheap labor, lower the prices of everything from farm produce to new homes, and leave consumers with a little more money in their pockets. So why is there such a discrepancy between the perception of immigrants' impact on the economy and the reality?\n    There are a number of familiar theories. Some argue that people are anxious and feel threatened by an inflow of new workers. Others highlight the strain that undocumented immigrants place on public services, like schools, hospitals, and jails. Still others emphasize the role of race, arguing that foreigners add to the nation's fears and insecurities. There's some truth to all these explanations, but they aren't quite sufficient.\n    To get a better understanding of what's going on, consider the way immigration's impact is felt. Though its overall effect may be positive, its costs and benefits are distributed unevenly. David Card, an economist at UC Berkeley, notes that the ones who profit most directly from immigrants' low-cost labor are businesses and employers—meatpacking plants in Nebraska, for instance, or agricultural businesses in California. Granted, these producers' savings probably translate into lower prices at the grocery store, but how many consumers make that mental connection at the checkout counter? As for the drawbacks of illegal immigration, these, too, are concentrated. Native low-skilled workers suffer most from the competition of foreign labor. According to a study by George Borjas, a Harvard economist, immigration reduced the wages of American high-school dropouts by 9% between 1980-2000.\n    Among high-skilled, better-educated employees, however, opposition was strongest in states with both high numbers of immigrants and relatively generous social services. What worried them most, in other words, was the fiscal (财政的)burden of immigration. That conclusion was reinforced by another finding: that their opposition appeared to soften when that fiscal burden decreased, as occurred with welfare reform in the 1990s, which curbed immigrants' access to certain benefits.\n    The irony is that for all the overexcited debate, the net effect of immigration is minimal. Even for those most acutely affected say, low-skilled workers, or California residents the impact isn't all that dramatic. \"The unpleasant voices have tended to dominate our perceptions,\" says Daniel Tichenor, a political science professor at the University of Oregon. \"But when all those factors are put together and the economists calculate the numbers, it ends up being a net positive, but a small one.\" Too bad most people don't realize it.","audioUrl":"","questionJson":[{"id":102985,"title":"What can we learn from the first paragraph?","textExplain":"定位：根据题干the first paragraph将本题定位于第一段。\n解析：第一段第二句说The American public overwhelmingly thinks they're bad，“绝大多数美国民众认为移民对经济没有好处”，第三句说Yet the consensus among most economists is that immigration … provides a small net boost to the economy，“然而大多数经济学家认为移民为经济带来了小幅度的增长”。即民众与经济学家在移民对经济的影响上的理解是不一样的，故D为正确选项。","videoExplainUrl":"","rightOpt":4,"userOpt":0,"answerJsons":[{"option":1,"content":"Whether immigrants are good or bad for the economy has been puzzling economists."},{"option":2,"content":"The American economy used to thrive on immigration but now it's a different story."},{"option":3,"content":"The consensus among economists is that immigration should not be encouraged."},{"option":4,"content":"The general public thinks differently from most economists on the impact of immigration."}]},{"id":102986,"title":"In what way does the author think ordinary Americans benefit from immigration?","textExplain":"定位：通过benefit 和immigration将本题定位于第一段第三句。\n解析：第一段第三句说Immigrants provide cheap labor, lower the prices of everything from farm produce to new homes, and leave consumers with a little more money in their pockets，“移民提供廉价劳动力，降低从农产品到新房中所需物品的价格，并让消费者省下更多的钱”。即B选项中“提供更便宜的消费商品”为正确答案。","videoExplainUrl":"","rightOpt":2,"userOpt":0,"answerJsons":[{"option":1,"content":"They can access all kinds of public services."},{"option":2,"content":"They can get consumer goods at lower prices."},{"option":3,"content":"They can mix with people of different cultures."},{"option":4,"content":"They can avoid doing much of the manual labor."}]},{"id":102987,"title":"Why do native low-skilled workers suffer most from illegal immigration?","textExplain":"定位：由题干中的native low-ski