gone ideologically overboard in their own ways. Since the 1980s, America has been increasingly clinging to the ideology of uncontrolled free markets and dismissing the role of government—following Ronald Regan’s idea that “government is not the solution to our problem; government is the problem. “Of course, when the markets came crashing down in 2007, it was decisive government intervention that saved the day. Despite this fact, many Americans are still strongly opposed to “ big government.”\n    If Americans could only free themselves from their antigovernment doctrine, they would begin to see that the America’s problems are not insoluble. A few sensible federal measures could put the country back on the right path. A simple consumption tax of, say, 5% would significantly reduce the country’s huge government deficit without damaging productivity. A small gasoline tax would help free America from its dependence on oil imports and create incentives for green energy development. In the same way, a significant reduction of wasteful agricultural subsidies could also lower the deficit. But in order to take advantage of these common-sense solutions, Americans will have to put aside their own attachment to the idea of smaller government and less regulation. American politicians will have to develop the courage to follow what is taught in all American public-policy schools: that there are good taxes and bad taxes. Asian countries have embraced this wisdom, and have built sound long-term fiscal (财政的) policies as a result.\n    Meanwhile, Europe has fallen prey to a different ideological trap: the belief that European governments would always have infinite resources and could continue borrowing as if there were no tomorrow. Unlike the Americans, who felt that the markets knew best, the Europeans failed to anticipate how the markets would react to their endless borrowing. Today, the European Union is creating a $580 billion fund to ward off sovereign collapse. This will buy the EU time, but it will not solve the bloc’s larger problem.","audioUrl":"","questionJson":[{"id":103010,"title":"What has contributed to the rapid economic growth in China and India?","textExplain":"定位：根据题干中growth in China and India定位到第二段第二、三句话。.\n解析：定位句说，However, once China began embracing free-market reforms in the 1980s, followed by India in the 1990s, both countries achieved rapid growth. “中国在20世纪80年代开始推行自由市场改革，印度在90年代紧跟其后，两国均实现了快速的增长”。后面一句说，Crucially, as they opened up their markets, they balanced market economy with sensible government direction，“至关重要的是，随着市场的开放，他们在市场经济和政府导向之间取得了平衡”。即市场经济和政府调控是中印经济快速发展的原因，故D选项为正确答案。","videoExplainUrl":"","rightOpt":4,"userOpt":0,"answerJsons":[{"option":1,"content":"Timely reform of government at all levels."},{"option":2,"content":"Heavy reliance on the hand of government."},{"option":3,"content":"Copying western-style economic behavior."},{"option":4,"content":"Free market plus government intervention."}]},{"id":103011,"title":"What does Ronald Reagan mean by saying “government is the problem” (line4, Para. 3)?","textExplain":"定位：根据题干中Ronald Reagan定位到第三段第二句话。\n解析：定位句说，Since the 1980s, America has been increasingly clinging to the ideology of uncontrolled free markets and dismissing the role of government—following Ronald Regan’s idea that “government is not the solution to our problem; government is the problem，“可知20世纪80年代以来，美国从上世纪80年代已经越来越迷恋于无约束的自由市场思维，李根总统说政府不能解决问题，政府本身就是个问题”。由此可知，美国人认为政府会阻碍经济发展，即B选项为正确答案。","videoExplainUrl":"","rightOpt":2,"userOpt":0,"answerJsons":[{"option":1,"content":"Government action is key to solving economic problems."},{"option":2,"content":"Government regulation hinders economic development."},{"option":3,"content":"Many social ills are caused by wrong government policies."},{"option":4,"content":"Many social problems arise from government’s inefficiency."}]},{"id":103012,"title":"What stopped the American economy from collapsing in 2007?","textExplain":"定位：根据题干中2007定位到第三段第三句话\n解析：定位句说，when the m